# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: egui-rust
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:egui-rust/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] A **graphics library** or **graphics API** is a program library designed to aid in rendering computer graphics to a monitor.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] This typically involves providing optimized versions of functions that handle common rendering tasks.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] This can be done purely in software and running on the CPU, common in embedded systems, or being hardware accelerated by a GPU, more common in PCs.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] By employing these functions, a program can assemble an image to be output to a monitor.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] This relieves the programmer of the task of creating and optimizing these functions, and allows them to focus on building the graphics program.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] Graphics libraries are mainly used in video games and simulations.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] The use of graphics libraries in connection with video production systems, such as Pixar RenderMan, is not covered here.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] Some APIs use Graphics Library (GL) in their name, notably OpenGL and WebGL.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] Dedicated graphics processors use RAM allocated directly to the graphics processor rather than the computer’s main system memory.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] This RAM is usually specifically selected with the expected sequential load of the graphics card in mind (see GDDR).
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] Sometimes systems with dedicated discrete graphics processors were called “DIS” systems in contrast to “UMA” systems.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] Technologies such as 3dfx's Scan-Line Interleave, Nvidia's SLI and NVLink, and AMD's CrossFire allow multiple graphics processors to simultaneously display images on one screen, increasing the computational power available for graphics processing.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] However, these technologies are becoming increasingly rare; most games do not utilize all the capabilities of multiple graphics processors since most users cannot afford them.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] Today, laptops and mini-PCs require powerful integrated graphics.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] In many cases, quality integrated graphics can replace a discrete graphics card, enhancing laptop portability and mini-PC compactness while maintaining performance.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] Integrated graphics processors (IGPU), integrated graphics, shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architectures (UMA) use part of the computer’s RAM rather than dedicated graphics memory.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] IGP may be integrated into the motherboard as part of its northbridge chipset or on a single chip (integrated circuit) with the central processor (e.g., AMD APU or Intel HD Graphics).
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] On some motherboards, AMD’s IGP may use sideport dedicated memory: a separate fixed block of high-performance memory allocated for use by the graphics processor.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] As of early 2007, computers with integrated graphics accounted for about 90% of all PC shipments.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] They are less expensive to implement than dedicated graphics processing but generally less powerful.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] Historically, integrated processing was considered unsuitable for 3D games or graphics-intensive applications but could run less resource-demanding programs like Adobe Flash.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] Examples of such IGPs include offerings from SiS and VIA around 2004.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] However, modern integrated graphics processors such as AMD Accelerated Processing Unit and Intel Graphics Technology (HD, UHD, Iris, Iris Pro, Iris Plus, and Xe-LP) can handle 2D graphics or undemanding 3D graphics.
[src:egui-rust/graphics-library] In systems with a “unified memory architecture” (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, PS5, and Xbox Series (among others), the CPU cores and GPU unit share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] without the use of extensive indirection – thus***immediate***– to retained resources.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] It does not preclude the use of double-buffering.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] Retained mode is an alternative approach.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] Historically, retained mode has been the dominant style in GUI libraries; however, both can coexist in the same library and are not necessarily exclusive in practice.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] In immediate mode, the scene (complete object model of the rendering primitives) is retained in the memory space of the client, instead of the graphics library.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] This implies that in an immediate mode application, the lists of graphical objects to be rendered are kept by the client and are not saved by the graphics library API.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] The application must re-issue all drawing commands required to describe the entire scene each time a new frame is required, regardless of actual changes.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] This method provides on the one hand a maximum of control and flexibility to the application program, but on the other hand it also generates continuous work load on the CPU.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] Examples of immediate mode rendering systems include Direct2D, OpenGL and Quartz.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] There are some immediate mode GUIs that are particularly suitable when used in conjunction with immediate mode rendering systems.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] Primitive vertex attribute data may be inserted frame by frame into a command buffer by a rendering API.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] This involves significant bandwidth and processor time (especially if the graphics processing unit is on a separate bus), but may be advantageous for data generated dynamically by the CPU.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] It is less common since the advent of increasingly versatile shaders, with which a graphics processing unit may generate increasingly complex effects without the need for CPU intervention.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] Graphical user interfaces traditionally use retained mode-style API design, but immediate mode GUIs instead use an immediate mode-style API design, in which user code directly specifies the GUI elements to draw in the user input loop.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] For example, rather than having a CreateButton() function that a user would call once to instantiate a button, an immediate-mode GUI API may have a DoButton() function which should be called whenever the button should be on screen.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] The technique was developed by Casey Muratori in 2002.
[src:egui-rust/immediate-mode-gui] Prominent implementations include Omar Cornut's Dear ImGui in C++, Nic Barker's Clay in C and Micha Mettke's Nuklear in C.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Memory errors were first considered in the context of resource management (computing) and time-sharing systems, in an effort to avoid problems such as fork bombs.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Developments were mostly theoretical until the Morris worm, which exploited a buffer overflow in fingerd.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] The field of computer security developed quickly thereafter, escalating with multitudes of new attacks such as the return-to-libc attack and defense techniques such as the non-executable stack and address space layout randomization.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Randomization prevents most buffer overflow attacks and requires the attacker to use heap spraying or other application-dependent methods to obtain addresses, although its adoption has been slow.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] However, deployments of the technology are typically limited to randomizing libraries and the location of the stack.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] In 2019, a Microsoft security engineer reported that 70% of all security vulnerabilities were caused by memory safety issues.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] In 2020, a team at Google similarly reported that 70% of all "severe security bugs" in Chromium were caused by memory safety problems.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Many other high-profile vulnerabilities and exploits in critical software have ultimately stemmed from a lack of memory safety, including Heartbleed and a long-standing privilege escalation bug in sudo.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] The pervasiveness and severity of vulnerabilities and exploits arising from memory safety issues have led several security researchers to describe identifying memory safety issues as "shooting fish in a barrel".
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Some modern high-level programming languages are memory-safe by default, though not completely since they only check their own code and not the system they interact with.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Automatic memory management in the form of garbage collection is the most common technique for preventing some of the memory safety problems, since it prevents common memory safety errors like use-after-free for all data allocated within the language runtime.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] However, the performance overhead of garbage collection makes these languages unsuitable for certain performance-critical applications.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] For languages that use manual memory management, memory safety is not usually guaranteed by the runtime.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Instead, memory safety properties must either be guaranteed by the compiler via static program analysis and automated theorem proving or carefully managed by the programmer at runtime.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] For example, the Rust programming language implements a borrow checker to ensure memory safety, while C and C++ provide no memory safety guarantees.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] The substantial amount of software written in C and C++ has motivated the development of external static analysis tools like Coverity, which offers static memory analysis for C.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] DieHard, its redesign DieHarder, and the Allinea Distributed Debugging Tool are special heap allocators that allocate objects in their own random virtual memory page, allowing invalid reads and writes to be stopped and debugged at the exact instruction that causes them.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Protection relies upon hardware memory protection and thus overhead is typically not substantial, although it can grow significantly if the program makes heavy use of allocation.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Randomization provides only probabilistic protection against memory errors, but can often be easily implemented in existing software by relinking the binary.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] The memcheck tool of Valgrind uses an instruction set simulator and runs the compiled program in a memory-checking virtual machine, providing guaranteed detection of a subset of runtime memory errors.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] However, it typically slows the program down by a factor of 40, and furthermore must be explicitly informed of custom memory allocators.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] With access to the source code, libraries exist that collect and track legitimate values for pointers ("metadata") and check each pointer access against the metadata for validity, such as the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] In general, memory safety can be safely assured using tracing garbage collection and the insertion of runtime checks on every memory access; this approach has overhead, but less than that of Valgrind.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] All garbage-collected languages take this approach.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] For C and C++, many tools exist that perform a compile-time transformation of the code to do memory safety checks at runtime, such as CheckPointer and AddressSanitizer which imposes an average slowdown factor of 2.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] BoundWarden is a new spatial memory enforcement approach that utilizes a combination of compile-time transformation and runtime concurrent monitoring techniques.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Fuzz testing is well-suited for finding memory safety bugs and is often used in combination with dynamic checkers such as AddressSanitizer.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Some lists may also include **race conditions** (concurrent reads/writes to shared memory) as being part of memory safety (e.g., for access control).
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] The Rust programming language prevents many kinds of memory-based race conditions by default, because it ensures there is at most one writer *or* one or more readers.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Many other programming languages, such as Java, do *not* automatically prevent memory-based race conditions, yet are still generally considered "memory safe" languages.
[src:egui-rust/memory-safety] Therefore, countering race conditions is generally *not* considered necessary for a language to be considered memory safe.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:egui-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:egui-rust/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
